# Civil Filing Client (20160922)

Version 2.2, C#

Application integrates with the New Jersey eCourts system [https://www.njcourts.gov/attorneys/ecourts.html] to file COMPLAINTS.

> "SubmitCivilFiling: Enables the user to file a new civil case. It accepts CivilFilingRequest as the input and CivilFilingResponse will be the output. On successful filing submission, the web service will return docket number and efiling sequence number. "

eCourts webservice is written in java. This all started back in September 2016. App written pretty quick to meet a fast approaching deadline. It's far from perfect, but has been running since 2016 with hardly any support. ;-)

Registration for eCourts: [https://portal.njcourts.gov/webe19/ecourtsweb/pages/home/home.faces]

A fun project might be to convert all this to some scripting language like powershell.

See Also [https://github.com/craignicholson/civilfiling_searchnotices]

Hope this helps someone!

## Requirements

- Microsoft Visual Studio
- Allow user to select multiple xml and pdf files to be sent to eCourts.
- Read in data in from XML file and post this data along with a pdf to the eCourts system.
- Log all messages to a file and a window for the user to review in case of errors.
- Archive a back up of the files to a daily folder when processing is complete.
- Log each files result in their own individual file for quick reasearch.
- Switch Production and Test EndPoints using the Settings on the menu.

## Tech Fun Stuff

- Implements its own Security Header to conform with the older java soap security model. [SecurityHeader.cs]
- Uses NLog to keep a daily log.txt file for monitoring and review.
- Logging and Tracing Soap/WCF Messages [https://rashimuddin.wordpress.com/2012/05/11/how-to-log-and-trace-wcf-soap-messages/] using System.ServiceModel.MessageLogging (Capturing soap request and response)
- MTOM encoding for file, set a max size <messageEncoding="Mtom" maxBufferSize="999999" maxReceivedMessageSize="999999">
- XML/Soap Integration

## Quick Start

- No installer is included, you will need access to Visual Studio to run this application
- Change the App.Config values for sharedListeners > initializeData data path, a file path where to write the Trace files.
- Run the App
- Make sure you running in Tests using url [https://dptng.njcourts.gov:2045/civilFilingWS_t]
- Attach File (..\TestFiles\Complaint_Test.xml)
- Click Send
- Read Results in App TextBox
- Review files in directory where xml and pdf files were initially located
- If successful, the files are archived to a folder with YYYYMMDD and a log file will be in the original folder where the xml and pdf were originally.
- Review the data in the Trace files (Traces.Detailed.xml, Traces.Request-Response.Messages.xml)

The first request tends to take several seconds and gets quicker as the eCourts webservice is used.

## How to use in production

You need to contact eCourts and setup an account and generate the required xml and pdf files. In the past most customers
were generating the xml files and would send the files to a ftp site (so I was told).

There is an alternate csv file support quickly coded and tested a few times. It was never ran in production like the xml file.
To create the xml file you can just copy the example file or use your programming lang tooling to help create the xml file.

If you are using this in production just remove the System.ServiceModel.MessageLogging stuff and add back when you have issues.
There is no need to always log the request and response. However, disk space is cheap so log away.

## Test Files Provided

See Folder TestFiles. Any pdf file will work for testing. Production requires the actual Complaint in in a pdf. If you are a law firm you know what this contains.

## Command Line Interface Example

User at own risk. We implemeted this quickly to automate the process but dropped it for some reason.

One can execute the application from the command line.  Here is an example  you can run from windows command prompt.

```cmd

C:\> cd "C:\CivilFilingClient\"
C:\CivilFilingClient> CivilFilingClient.exe "888888005" "P@ssword" "https://dptng.njcourts.gov:2045/civilFilingWS_t" "C:\Files\Complaint_Test.xml" 

C:\CivilFilingClient> CivilFilingClient.exe "888888005" "P@ssword" "https://dptng.njcourts.gov:2045/civilFilingWS_t" "C:\Files\Complaint_Test.xml" 

```

Requires the pdf to be in the same folder as the xml file.

The parameters to pass in are the following:

- Username
- Password
- EndPoint {testing or production}
- xml full file Path

There is no output back to the command line.  Review the log files for the results.

## Configuration Bindings (CivilFilingClient.exe.config)

The soap endpoint requires a specific soap header with credentials.  All
communication is over https so the credentials are encrypted as long there is no MITM.

This header is detailed in the eCourts integration documentation.

```xml
<bindings>
  <basicHttpBinding>
    <binding name="CivilFilingWSPortBinding" >
      <security mode="Transport">
        <transport clientCredentialType="None" />
      </security>
    </binding>
    <binding name="CivilFilingWSService_CivilFilingWSPort" messageEncoding="Mtom">
      <security mode="Transport">
        <transport clientCredentialType="None" />
      </security>
    </binding>
  </basicHttpBinding>
</bindings>
<client>
  <endpoint address="https://dptng.njcourts.gov:2045/civilFilingWS_t"
      binding="basicHttpBinding"
      bindingConfiguration="CivilFilingWSService_CivilFilingWSPort"
      contract="CivilFilingServiceReference.CivilFilingWS"
      name="CivilFilingWSPort">
    <headers>
      <wsse:Security xmlns:wsse="http://docs.oasis-open.org/wss/2004/01/oasis-200401-wss-wssecurity-secext-1.0.xsd">
        <wsse:UsernameToken Id="unt_20">
          <wsse:Username>**********</wsse:Username>
          <wsse:Password Type="http://docs.oasis-open.org/wss/2004/01/oasis-200401-wss-username-token-profile-1.0#PasswordText">********</wsse:Password>
        </wsse:UsernameToken>
      </wsse:Security>
    </headers>
  </endpoint>
</client>

```

### Error Messages

```txt

Description: Rejected by policy. (from client). -> Username or password is wrong.

```xml
<env:Envelope xmlns:env="http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/soap/envelope/">
    <s:Header xmlns:s="http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/soap/envelope/"></s:Header>
    <env:Body>
        <env:Fault>
            <faultcode xmlns="">env:Client</faultcode>
            <faultstring xmlns="">Rejected by policy. (from client)</faultstring>
        </env:Fault>
    </env:Body>
</env:Envelope>
```

List of Errors encountered

- Code: ECCV100 Description: Document Redaction Indicator should be Y
- Code: ECCV110 Description: Attorney's Client Reference number should be a numeric value [0-9]  
- Code: ECCV110 Description: Party name can only contain A-Z, a-z, 0-9, space, period, dash, $, ?, !, (, ), #, %, comma, slash, single quote, &
- Code: ECCV110 Description: Please provide a valid Case Action (3 chars, if 28 make it 028)
- Code: ECCV200 Description: Please provide a valid Firm/ branch ID
- Code: ECCV200 Description: Branch Id cannot be null or empty
- Code: ECCV210 Description: Error Occurred, Pelase contact HelpDesk (Attorney id passed in the input request is incorrect. It must be 9 digits)
- Code: ECCV210 Description: Please provide pdf extension to the document name
- Code: ECCV300 Error Occurred, Pelase contact HelpDesk
- Code: ECCV310 Error Occurred, Pelase contact HelpDesk
- Code: ECCV320 Error Occurred, Pelase contact HelpDesk
- Code: ECCV400 Error Occurred, Pelase contact HelpDesk
- Code: ECCV410 Error Occurred, Pelase contact HelpDesk
- Code: ECCV500 Description: Filing submitted scuccessfully
- Code: ECCV520 Description: An error occurred during the submission of your filing. Please contact the help desk at 609-421-6100.

Need an update on ECCV520 description and the resolution.

Additional Messages we have recieved:

The eCourt web service was down and not processing the submissions.  The request will be accepted and return a sequence number
but no Docket Number.  You will have to resend this submission once the web service is back up.
eFiling seq number:SCP20161007426

## HTTP timeout

```txt
The HTTP request to 'https://dptng.njcourts.gov:2045/civilFilingWS_t' has exceeded the allotted timeout of 00:00:59.9680000. 
The time allotted to this operation may have been a portion of a longer timeout.
```

When you see this error communication with the webservice was disconnected before
the submission could be created or the web service (eCourts) could respond back to the client (CivilFilingClient).

### File Name Valid characters

A-Z, a-z, 0-9, .

### Valid characters

A-Z, a-z, 0-9, space, period, dash, $, ?, !, (, ), #, %, comma, slash, single quote, &

Inspecting the soap message using the trace file with the System.ServiceModel.MessageLogging setup in the .config file.

------------
You can inspect the soap message by creating an endpoint and sending the request to the endpoint.
You will need to comment out the security in the App.config.

## Logging

Logs are written for each run and are located in the logs folder inside the applications folder.
The logs are setup to maintain up to 365 days of logs.

## Backup of configs

### NLog

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
<nlog xmlns="http://www.nlog-project.org/schemas/NLog.xsd"
      xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
      throwExceptions="true">

  <!-- 
  See http://nlog-project.org/wiki/Configuration_file 
  for information on customizing logging rules and outputs.
   --> 
  <targets>
        <target 
            name="logfile" 
            xsi:type="File" 
            fileName="${basedir}/logs/log.txt" 
            layout="${level} | ${longdate} | ${message} | ${callsite:fileName=true} ${onexception:inner=${exception:format=tostring,StackTrace}}"
            archiveFileName="${basedir}/logs/log.{#}.txt"
            archiveEvery="Day"
            archiveNumbering="Rolling"
            maxArchiveFiles="365"
            concurrentWrites="true" 
        />
  </targets>

  <rules>
    <logger name="*" minlevel="Info" writeTo="logfile" />
  </rules>
</nlog>
```
